an fetch email and calendar. We can look for a script in the workspace directory and run it.\n\n 2. If we don't find one, we might have to return an error.\n\n But note: the user's request is in the context of a cron job, so they must have set up the necessary access.\n\n Since we don't have a clear way, we should try to use the `exec` tool to run a command that the user might have set up.\n\n However, without knowing the exact command, we can only guess. We might try:\n\n   - For email: `openclaw email list --since today`\n   - For calendar: `openclaw calendar today`\n\n But these are hypothetical commands. We must rely on the user having set up such commands.\n\n Alternatively, we can look in the workspace for a script called `morning_status.sh` or similar.\n\n Let's check the workspace for a script:\n\n   - We can use `exec` to run `ls` and see if there is a script.\n\n But note: the cron job is running and we must return a summary. We are not in the main session, so we cannot ask the user.\n\n We must try to do our best.\n\n Steps:\n\n 1. Check for the existence of a script in the workspace that handles this.\n\n 2. If found, run it and capture the output.\n\n 3. If not found, try to run a default command (if we have one).\n\n However, we don't have a default command. So we must return an error.\n\n Since we are in a cron job, we must output the result as plain text.\n\n Let's assume the user has set up a script at `~/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/morning_status.sh`.\n\n We can:\n\n   - Check if the file exists by trying to read it? But we don't want to run it by reading. We want to execute.\n\n   - We can use `exec` to run the script if it exists.\n\n How to check existence? We can run:\n\n   ```bash\n   if [ -f \"/home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/morning_status.sh\" ]; then\n     /home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/morning_status.sh\n   else\n     echo \"Script not found.\"\n   fi\n   ```\n\n But note: we are in a function call. We can do:\n\n   First, check if the script exists by using the `read` tool on the script file? But that would read the content, not run it.\n\n   Alternatively, we can run an `exec` command that checks and runs.\n\n We can do:\n\n   ```json\n   {\n     \"command\": \"test -f /home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/morning_status.sh && /home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/morning_status.sh || echo 'No script found for morning status.'\"\n   }\n   ```\n\n But note: the `exec` tool runs in the shell, so we can do that.\n\n However, if the script doesn't exist, we must provide a fallback.\n\n But without a script, we cannot get the email and calendar.\n\n Given the time constraints and the fact that this is a cron job, we must return a message that the script is not set up.\n\n Alternatively, we can try to use the `feishu` tools if the user's email and calendar are on Feishu. But the task doesn't specify.\n\n Since we don't have enough context, we will output an error message.\n\n Let's run:\n\n   - We'll try to run the script if it exists, else we output an error.\n\n We'll use the `exec` tool to run the command above.\n\n But note: the `exec` tool returns the output of the command.\n\n We'll call the `exec` tool with the command string.\n\n However, note that the workspace is at `/home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace`, so the script path is absolute.\n\n Let's do it.\n\n But note: the cron job is running and we must return the summary. We are making a tool call that will block until the command runs.\n\n We'll run:\n\n   ```json\n   {\n     \"command\": \"if [ -f \\\"/home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/morning_status.sh\\\" ]; then /home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/morning_status.sh; else echo 'Error: The morning status script is not found.'; fi\"\n   }\n   ```\n\n We are in the `exec` tool, so we can run this.\n\n But note: the `exec` tool may require elevated permissions? We are running in the cron job context, so we have the same permissions as the OpenClaw p